<emphasis id="E26F4025AEC139E4058B729705C1EAC3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="207">Y.M. Shui et al. B2018-183</emphasis>
(KUN).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CE5C605624D7101653CA40BD5710C818" pageId="0" pageNumber="207" type="notes">
<paragraph id="4BBEEC4241F76AE79CE15DF40E2A8516" pageId="0" pageNumber="207">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DCC836EF59E1D16E1FCA7002C7F0D97E" pageId="0" pageNumber="207">
The new species appeared as 
<taxonomicName id="53B0738499B5C4E0D11888C944DEDA4B" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="Paraboea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Paraboea auriculata" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="207" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="auriculata">
<emphasis id="5160D49EC6997EA1CC05CE63C723F6CD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="207">Paraboea auriculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Y.M. Shui &amp; W.H. Chen (nom. nud.) because of its winged petioles in 
<bibRefCitation id="62ECEA750EA26DE0E50BA5711E3A0A39" author="Shui, YM" journalOrPublisher="Edinburgh Journal of Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="207" refId="B10" refString="Shui, YM, Chen, WH, 2006. Seed Plants of the Karst Region in China. Vol. 1, Southeast Yunnan. Science Press, Beijing, 173-174." title="Seed Plants of the Karst Region in China. Vol. 1, Southeast Yunnan. Science Press, Beijing, 173 - 174." year="2006">Shui and Chen (2006)</bibRefCitation>
. However, we decided to name it as 
<taxonomicName id="322A4C9B3D284EDEE1E208A38DC95064" authorityName="Y. M. Shui &amp; W. H. Chen" authorityYear="2020" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="Paraboea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Paraboea myriantha" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="207" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="myriantha">
<emphasis id="6A35347DF54DA7531C82CFED4BC0B6D0" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="207">Paraboea myriantha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, after careful comparison of references and type specimens with similar species, 
<taxonomicName id="0B8A644EE1EC3F456828899407147600" genus="P." lsidName="P. glutinosa" pageId="0" pageNumber="207" rank="species" species="glutinosa">
<emphasis id="3956EC91C533A94FF3EF1F20BACFD6DF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="207">P. glutinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Hand.-Mazz.) K.Y.Pan and 
<taxonomicName id="4A4E61F9659C57C9E1121FE3FDEA20FF" genus="P." lsidName="P. thorelii" pageId="0" pageNumber="207" rank="species" species="thorelii">
<emphasis id="C03B4BB3E4BFA4C322D5B60078A92269" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="207">P. thorelii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Pellegr.) B.L.Burtt. The new species is similar to the above two species on winged leaves and compound dichasia, but distinguished by corolla lobes (shape) and tubes (shape and indumenti) and glandular filament, which are described in diagnostics (Figure 
<figureCitation id="EB465CD1635C18942DD8AACABCDA519B" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Paraboea myriantha Y. M. Shui &amp; W. H. Chen, sp. nov. (A, C-G, J) and its similar species P. glutinosa (B, H, I) A, B habitat C abaxial surface of leaf D flower bud E lateral view of flower F bird view of flower G, H front view of flower I lateral view of flower J flower and fruits (A and C photographed by Gui-Liang Zhang and all the others by Yu-Min Shui)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.157.32534.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/446110" pageId="0" pageNumber="207">2</figureCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="DB049C1DE954B42A55C08B7B309C4653" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1017/S0960428608005106" author="Xu, ZR" journalOrPublisher="Edinburgh Journal of Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="207" pagination="161 - 347" refId="B20" refString="Xu, ZR, Burtt, BL, Skog, LE, Middleton, DJ, 2008. A revision of Paraboea (Gesneriaceae). Edinburgh Journal of Botany 65 (2): 161 - 347, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1017/S0960428608005106" title="A revision of Paraboea (Gesneriaceae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1017/S0960428608005106" volume="65" year="2008">Xu et al. 2008</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="0EE3B67016F6AA34B4F35FDBC4F701D2" author="Vu, XP" journalOrPublisher="Guihaia" pageId="0" pageNumber="207" pagination="288 - 290" refId="B13" refString="Vu, XP, Do, TX, Wen, F, Wei, YG, 2011. Two occurrence taxa in Paraboea (C.B. Clarke) Ridl. (Gesneriaceae) for flora of Vietnam. Guihaia 31 (3): 288 - 290" title="Two occurrence taxa in Paraboea (C. B. Clarke) Ridl. (Gesneriaceae) for flora of Vietnam." volume="31" year="2011">Vu et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
). Furthermore, 
<taxonomicName id="929CAF2EFBE2A28A776D0F5A6A55DB6C" genus="P." lsidName="P. glutinosa" pageId="0" pageNumber="207" rank="species" species="glutinosa">
<emphasis id="9AA9E2B5AC1238B08105AD3621D4C4D5" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="207">P. glutinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distributed in South China, 
<taxonomicName id="E1A134BE9CDEB6385D7F1B1C8AE1F126" genus="P." lsidName="P. thorelii" pageId="0" pageNumber="207" rank="species" species="thorelii">
<emphasis id="C03D02584C35A31F22ACF37D0EB723A1" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="207">P. thorelii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in South Laos (type locality) and North Vietnam, but the new species we proposed seems geographically distributed between the above two similar species. So, the future molecular work in the context of the whole genus may reveal if the above three species become a species complex with obvious geographical replacement.
</paragraph>
